abstract: EVENTS    ''GONE FISHING,'' Robert F. Wagner Jr. Park, Battery Park City, Lower Manhattan. Catch-and-release fishing today, 11:30 a.m. to 1:30 p.m. Free; equipment provided. Sponsored by the Battery Park City Parks Conservancy. Information: (212) 267-9700.

A selective listing by critics of The Times of noteworthy pop and jazz concerts in the New York metropolitan region this weekend. * denotes a highly recommended concert.    J. D. ALLEN QUARTET, Jazz Gallery, 290 Hudson Street, at Spring Street, South Village, (212) 242-1063. A young tenor player who's been heard in Cindy Blackman and Duane Eubanks's bands; here he leads a first-class group, with the pianist Orrin Evans, the bassist Eric Revis and the drummer Ali Jackson. Tomorrow at 9 and 10:30; cover charge is $12, $10 for members (Ben Ratliff).

abstract: A selective listing by critics of The Times of noteworthy pop and jazz concerts in the New York metropolitan region this weekend. * denotes a highly recommended concert.    * JOSÉ ALBERTO'S TÍPICA 73 REUNION, Copacabana, 560 West 34th Street, Manhattan, (212) 239-2672. In the late 1970's and early 80's, the high-flying Dominican salsa singer (and whistler) José Alberto (El Canario) led Típica 73, a group that linked salsa with its Cuban heritage. This show reunites him with an all-star band that includes Alfredo de la Fé on violin, Sonny Bravo on piano, Mario Rivera on saxophones and Nelson González on guitar. Tomorrow night after 10; general admission is $25, table seats $35, plus a two-drink minimum (Jon Pareles).
lead_paragraph: A selective listing by critics of The Times of noteworthy pop and jazz concerts in the New York metropolitan region this weekend. * denotes a highly recommended concert.

abstract: A selective listing by critics of The Times of noteworthy pop and jazz concerts in the New York metropolitan region this weekend. * denotes a highly recommended concert.    ANIMAL COLLECTIVE, Tonic, 107 Norfolk Street, near Delancey Street, Lower East Side, (212) 358-7503. The Animal Collective, featuring Avey Tare, Panda Bear, Geologist and Deaken, has been making whimsical, convoluted studio albums full of odd electronic noises and childlike delight. It shares the bill with Espers and Gang Gang Dance. Sunday night at 8; admission is $8 (Jon Pareles).

abstract: EVENTS    P.S. 11 BENEFIT, Chelsea Market, Ninth and Tenth Avenues, between 15th and 16th Streets. Food and drink sampling from more than 20 restaurants, including Boulud, Amy's Bread, Hale and Hearty Soup, and the Chelsea Market Basket. Today, 6 to 9 p.m. Admisssion, $30. Information: (212) 496-4520.    NEW YORK ASIAN FILM FESTIVAL, Anthology Film Archives, 32 Second Avenue, at Second Street, East Village. With more than 20 films from Korea, India, Hong Kong, Taiwan, Thailand and Japan. Through May 26. Screenings this weekend today at 6:30, 9 and 11:30 p.m.; tomorrow at 2, 4, 6:15, 9 and 11:30 p.m.; and Sunday at 2, 4:15, 6:45 and 9:15 p.m. Admission, $8. Information: (212) 592-3259; www.subwaycinema.com.

A selective listing by critics of The Times of noteworthy pop and jazz concerts in the New York metropolitan region this weekend. * denotes a highly recommended concert.    * AARKTICA, Galapagos, 70 North Sixth Street, Williamsburg, Brooklyn, (718) 782-5188. Aarktica's songs are extended reveries, built on loops of guitars and drums and occasional voices. The musical elements hover and circle, float by or bristle with distortion, as the songs drift through serenity and trouble. Tomorrow night at 7; admission is $8 (Jon Pareles).
